00:12:21,220 --> 00:12:23,680
same kind of probability distributions

280
00:12:23,680 --> 00:12:28,160
and how they depend on the orientation of the polarizers.

281
00:12:29,640 --> 00:12:31,430
I don't think anybody has

282
00:12:31,430 --> 00:12:33,220
ever successfully designed such a thing,

283
00:12:33,380 --> 00:12:35,720
at least not in any great generality,

284
00:12:36,960 --> 00:12:40,140
that would do the right thing to polarize photons.

285
00:12:41,560 --> 00:12:42,640
By design,

286
00:12:42,640 --> 00:12:44,540
I mean design a classical apparatus

287
00:12:44,540 --> 00:12:46,080
which would do the right thing.

288
00:12:46,380 --> 00:12:47,620
So there are only two possibilities.

289
00:12:48,480 --> 00:12:52,380
The photon either appears to be polarized up

290
00:12:52,380 --> 00:12:56,340
or appears to be polarized horizontally when you detect it.

291
00:12:56,500 --> 00:12:59,120
When you detect it with a horizontal polarizer,

292
00:12:59,160 --> 00:13:00,800
it either goes through or it doesn't go through.

293
00:13:01,100 --> 00:13:02,850
So you would be likely to

294
00:13:02,850 --> 00:13:04,600
say there's only two possible states

295
00:13:04,600 --> 00:13:05,480
for the photon.

296
00:13:05,900 --> 00:13:07,180
On the other hand,

297
00:13:07,180 --> 00:13:08,720
there's more than two possible states.

298
00:13:09,310 --> 00:13:11,920
There's a continuum of possible states for the photon.

299
00:13:12,160 --> 00:13:14,220
You can polarize it in any direction.

300
00:13:14,920 --> 00:13:17,620
And so we have a kind

301
00:13:17,620 --> 00:13:20,320
of conflict between discreteness and continuity.

302
00:13:21,280 --> 00:13:23,940
Continuous direction in which the photon can be polarized,

303
00:13:24,280 --> 00:13:26,420
but when we monitor it and we detect it,

304
00:13:26,520 --> 00:13:28,760
there are only two possible states,

305
00:13:28,760 --> 00:13:30,840
one or the other.

306
00:13:30,980 --> 00:13:33,800
And that's the mystery of quantum mechanics.

307
00:13:36,860 --> 00:13:39,840
It's a conflict between symmetry on the one hand

308
00:13:39,840 --> 00:13:42,120
and discreteness on the other hand.

309
00:13:44,360 --> 00:13:44,960
Okay,

310
00:13:44,960 --> 00:13:46,610
so we were beginning to

311
00:13:46,610 --> 00:13:48,260
set up the theory of polarization.

312
00:13:52,180 --> 00:13:53,200
As I said,

313
00:13:53,200 --> 00:13:55,980
it is probably the simplest context

314
00:13:55,980 --> 00:13:57,820
in which to study quantum mechanics.

315
00:13:58,560 --> 00:14:01,170
It doesn't have the full

316
00:14:01,170 --> 00:14:03,780
complexity of all of quantum mechanics,

317
00:14:03,780 --> 00:14:05,600
but it's the simplest quantum mechanical system.

318
00:14:06,800 --> 00:14:09,020
So let's now label the quantum

319
00:14:09,020 --> 00:14:11,240
states of the polarization of a photon.

320
00:14:11,440 --> 00:14:13,340
I will make this phrase shorter.

321
00:14:13,460 --> 00:14:15,440
I will simply say the quantum states of a photon,

322
00:14:15,680 --> 00:14:16,940
but I mean its polarization.

323
00:14:17,720 --> 00:14:18,460
All right,

324
00:14:18,460 --> 00:14:19,740
it can be polarized horizontally.

325
00:14:20,040 --> 00:14:20,640
Incidentally,

326
00:14:20,640 --> 00:14:25,140
there is no difference between being polarized horizontally

327
00:14:25,140 --> 00:14:28,560
to the right or polarized horizontally to the left.

328
00:14:28,820 --> 00:14:30,600
That's why I tend to

329
00:14:30,600 --> 00:14:32,380
draw double arrows on the polarization.

330
00:14:33,780 --> 00:14:36,400
There's no difference between being polarized to the right

331
00:14:36,400 --> 00:14:37,740
or polarized to the left.

332
00:14:38,000 --> 00:14:39,660
If you think about it for a moment,

333
00:14:39,780 --> 00:14:42,420
an electromagnetic wave will oscillate up and down,

334
00:14:42,640 --> 00:14:44,760
and so there's no sense in which you can say

335
00:14:44,760 --> 00:14:49,280
the polarization is vertically up versus vertically down,

336
00:14:49,819 --> 00:14:52,160
and the photon inherits that fact.

337
00:14:53,599 --> 00:14:54,040
Polarization,

338
00:14:54,040 --> 00:14:55,880
you can think of a polarization vector,

339
00:14:56,020 --> 00:14:57,200
but it kind of has two ends.

340
00:14:58,040 --> 00:14:59,680
There's no sense in which it points

341
00:14:59,680 --> 00:15:01,320
to the right rather than to the left,

342
00:15:01,320 --> 00:15:02,970
but there is a sense in

343
00:15:02,970 --> 00:15:04,620
which it's pointing horizontal rather than vertical.

344
00:15:05,000 --> 00:15:06,560
So in some way,

345
00:15:06,560 --> 00:15:08,840
it's simpler than the spin one

346
00:15:08,840 --> 00:15:11,120
half system you looked at before.

347
00:15:11,180 --> 00:15:11,600
Well,

348
00:15:11,600 --> 00:15:15,480
they're actually quite isomorphic to each other.

349
00:15:15,960 --> 00:15:17,560
They're completely parallel,

350
00:15:17,560 --> 00:15:19,400
completely identical mathematics,

351
00:15:20,040 --> 00:15:22,400
and the reason for not doing it this time,

352
00:15:22,400 --> 00:15:22,820
the spin,

353
00:15:23,040 --> 00:15:24,300
is because I did it last time.

354
00:15:25,020 --> 00:15:26,180
That's the main reason.

355
00:15:27,920 --> 00:15:30,820
Some people find it a little easier to visualize

356
00:15:31,339 --> 00:15:32,700
the polarization of a photon.

357
00:15:35,660 --> 00:15:38,220
They're identical systems quantum mechanically,

358
00:15:38,699 --> 00:15:41,020
and so we don't really need to distinguish that.

359
00:15:41,120 --> 00:15:41,180
Well,

360
00:15:41,180 --> 00:15:42,020
okay,

361
00:15:42,020 --> 00:15:42,480
let's go on.

362
00:15:42,960 --> 00:15:43,500
All right,

363
00:15:43,500 --> 00:15:44,240
we're going to call that,

364
00:15:44,380 --> 00:15:46,640
we're going to give that the name x.

365
00:15:47,420 --> 00:15:49,320
That's the ket vector x.

366
00:15:49,440 --> 00:15:51,720
It represents a photon polarized horizontally.

367
00:15:52,960 --> 00:15:54,880
And another way that we can label it,

368
00:15:55,180 --> 00:15:56,920
I'm going to take these arrows off.

369
00:15:57,120 --> 00:15:59,040
I get awfully tired of drawing arrows,

370
00:15:59,300 --> 00:16:00,840
and they serve no purpose.

371
00:16:01,320 --> 00:16:01,540
However,

372
00:16:01,540 --> 00:16:05,320
since there's no sense of direction along the arrow,

373
00:16:07,100 --> 00:16:10,660
and I'll also label that one zero.

374
00:16:13,319 --> 00:16:15,920
Another representation of the,

375
00:16:16,060 --> 00:16:16,780
oh,

376
00:16:16,780 --> 00:16:17,400
incidentally,

377
00:16:17,400 --> 00:16:19,140
the vector space of states

378
00:16:19,140 --> 00:16:20,640
is clearly two-dimensional,

379
00:16:20,820 --> 00:16:24,020
since there are only two possibilities for the polarization.

380
00:16:25,040 --> 00:16:26,700
Two possibilities for the polarization,

381
00:16:29,060 --> 00:16:30,500
x or y,

382
00:16:35,560 --> 00:16:39,520
and we'll label y zero one.

383
00:16:41,480 --> 00:16:42,140
All right,

384
00:16:42,140 --> 00:16:43,880
so several different representations

385
00:16:44,840 --> 00:16:47,800
to label the states of the photon polarization.

386
00:16:50,180 --> 00:16:50,740
Yes?

387
00:16:51,620 --> 00:16:53,060
Is that totally arbitrary,

388
00:16:53,060 --> 00:16:54,020
one and zero,

389
00:16:54,120 --> 00:16:55,160
to be anything else,

390
00:16:55,160 --> 00:16:55,400
or?

391
00:16:56,420 --> 00:16:56,980
No,

392
00:16:56,980 --> 00:16:58,100
it's not totally arbitrary.

393
00:16:58,100 --> 00:17:02,820
We want these vectors to be normalized.

394
00:17:03,480 --> 00:17:04,700
Sums of the squares of the

395
00:17:04,700 --> 00:17:05,920
components should add up to one.

396
00:17:06,319 --> 00:17:08,319
That's one of the rules about state vectors.

397
00:17:08,480 --> 00:17:10,619
That corresponds to the total probability

398
00:17:11,160 --> 00:17:12,800
for a state adding up to one.

399
00:17:13,599 --> 00:17:15,880
We want them to be orthogonal to each other.

400
00:17:17,319 --> 00:17:19,099
These two vectors are clearly orthogonal.

401
00:17:20,020 --> 00:17:21,680
Multiply the top by the top,

402
00:17:21,680 --> 00:17:23,319
plus the bottom by the bottom.

403
00:17:24,099 --> 00:17:24,579
Incidentally,

404
00:17:24,579 --> 00:17:26,220
in order to take the inner product,

405
00:17:26,220 --> 00:17:28,280
you should complex conjugate one of them,

406
00:17:28,980 --> 00:17:31,740
but the complex conjugate of the bottom one is itself.

407
00:17:32,280 --> 00:17:34,820
So it's one times zero plus zero times one.

408
00:17:35,960 --> 00:17:36,520
x,

409
00:17:36,520 --> 00:17:39,360
y equals zero.

410
00:17:40,740 --> 00:17:41,620
They're orthogonal.

411
00:17:42,020 --> 00:17:42,980
They're normalized.

412
00:17:43,160 --> 00:17:44,300
They form a basis.

413
00:17:45,940 --> 00:17:46,500
Now,

414
00:17:46,500 --> 00:17:47,820
it's not completely...

415
00:17:48,560 --> 00:17:49,700
In some sense,

416
00:17:49,700 --> 00:17:51,220
you've chosen your axes

417
00:17:51,220 --> 00:17:52,800
so that those will be normal.

418
00:17:53,120 --> 00:17:53,380
Yes,

419
00:17:53,380 --> 00:17:54,940
I have.

420
00:17:57,220 --> 00:17:57,720
Now,

421
00:17:57,720 --> 00:17:58,860
I could have...

422
00:17:59,920 --> 00:18:03,720
We will see that these vectors are somewhat ambiguous.

423
00:18:04,620 --> 00:18:06,860
We're going to calculate the things which really count,

424
00:18:06,920 --> 00:18:08,640
and when we calculate what really count,

425
00:18:08,640 --> 00:18:09,340
namely probabilities,

426
00:18:10,100 --> 00:18:12,300
we'll find out that we can't,

427
00:18:12,300 --> 00:18:12,900
for example,

428
00:18:13,440 --> 00:18:15,740
distinguish this vector and this vector.

429
00:18:16,140 --> 00:18:19,120
The fact that there's something in the first place

430
00:18:19,120 --> 00:18:21,460
and nothing in the second place is the important thing,

431
00:18:21,990 --> 00:18:23,475
and the other important thing is that

432
00:18:23,475 --> 00:18:24,960
the sums of the squares of them

433
00:18:24,960 --> 00:18:25,720
add up to...

434
00:18:26,360 --> 00:18:28,220
Sums of the squares of the

435
00:18:28,220 --> 00:18:30,080
two components add up to one.

436
00:18:31,200 --> 00:18:34,900
But this is a convenient basis of the vectors

437
00:18:36,120 --> 00:18:38,080
which represent the two states.

438
00:18:39,720 --> 00:18:40,300
Okay?

439
00:18:40,440 --> 00:18:45,440
We also said that we could define an observable.

440
00:18:45,720 --> 00:18:48,380
An observable means the thing that we measure

441
00:18:48,960 --> 00:18:51,780
or that we record in our little book.

442
00:18:52,120 --> 00:18:54,100
We send a lot of photons through.

443
00:18:54,100 --> 00:18:56,440
If a photon goes through the apparatus,

444
00:18:57,040 --> 00:18:59,400
we say plus one.

445
00:18:59,660 --> 00:19:01,460
If it doesn't go through the apparatus,

446
00:19:01,460 --> 00:19:02,800
we say minus one.

447
00:19:03,020 --> 00:19:03,500
Now,

448
00:19:03,500 --> 00:19:03,720
there,

449
00:19:03,720 --> 00:19:05,240
there's absolutely nothing unique.

450
00:19:05,880 --> 00:19:07,940
I could have said seven and twelve.

451
00:19:08,700 --> 00:19:09,920
Anything I like,

452
00:19:09,920 --> 00:19:12,400
just to distinguish the two possibilities,

453
00:19:12,920 --> 00:19:16,360
one and minus one are a nice pair of numbers

454
00:19:16,360 --> 00:19:17,960
that they're easy to remember,

455
00:19:18,140 --> 00:19:20,220
and there's no particular significance

456
00:19:20,220 --> 00:19:22,300
to choosing one and minus one.

457
00:19:23,500 --> 00:19:24,740
It's easy to remember,

458
00:19:24,740 --> 00:19:26,560
has a nice symmetry to it.

459
00:19:26,900 --> 00:19:30,600
And so what we'll say is that the X polarization,

460
00:19:31,500 --> 00:19:33,620
we'll say has polarization plus,

461
00:19:34,120 --> 00:19:37,040
and the Y polarization has polarization minus.

462
00:19:37,800 --> 00:19:38,280
Again,

463
00:19:38,280 --> 00:19:39,340
what I mean by that is

464
00:19:39,340 --> 00:19:40,400
we send a lot of photons

465
00:19:40,400 --> 00:19:41,900
through an X polarizer.

466
00:19:42,400 --> 00:19:43,580
If they pass through,

467
00:19:43,580 --> 00:19:46,320
each time a photon passes through the X polarizer,

468
00:19:46,380 --> 00:19:48,040
we write down a little plus in our notebook.

469
00:19:48,440 --> 00:19:50,310
Each time it is reflected

470
00:19:50,310 --> 00:19:52,180
or whatever else happens to it,

471
00:19:52,180 --> 00:19:53,700
we write down a little minus,

472
00:19:53,900 --> 00:19:56,640
and then we can take statistics,

473
00:19:57,180 --> 00:19:58,900
we can define the observable quantity

474
00:19:58,900 --> 00:20:00,620
in the way that I said,

475
00:20:00,800 --> 00:20:06,180
and label it or associate it

476
00:20:06,180 --> 00:20:08,560
with a quantum mechanical observable.

477
00:20:08,700 --> 00:20:10,900
A quantum mechanical observable is an operator.

478
00:20:11,680 --> 00:20:13,320
I'll put a little hat on it.

479
00:20:13,520 --> 00:20:15,440
If I forget to put a hat on it,

480
00:20:16,660 --> 00:20:19,180
as long as it's this big double P here,

481
00:20:19,380 --> 00:20:20,980
it means an operator.

482
00:20:22,180 --> 00:20:26,480
It's an operator whose eigenvectors are X and Y,

483
00:20:26,760 --> 00:20:29,400
or this one and this one,

484
00:20:30,400 --> 00:20:32,890
and it has eigenvalue plus one

485
00:20:32,890 --> 00:20:35,380
for X and minus one for Y.

486
00:20:36,480 --> 00:20:37,340
That's unique.

487
00:20:42,040 --> 00:20:42,600
Abstractly,

488
00:20:42,600 --> 00:20:44,580
we know how it acts on any vector,

489
00:20:44,740 --> 00:20:46,930
because any vector can be

490
00:20:46,930 --> 00:20:49,120
linearly expanded in X and Y,

491
00:20:49,360 --> 00:20:52,060
but here's the state.

492
00:20:52,860 --> 00:20:54,320
This is equal to X,

493
00:20:55,060 --> 00:20:59,720
and P on Y is equal to minus Y.

494
00:21:00,340 --> 00:21:03,380
The eigenvalues are plus one and minus one,

495
00:21:03,540 --> 00:21:05,660
and I'm going to label this thing here

496
00:21:05,660 --> 00:21:08,440
just to indicate that it's a polarizer,

497
00:21:08,480 --> 00:21:11,800
that it represents polarization in the XY plane.

498
00:21:12,240 --> 00:21:14,000
I'm going to put a little symbol here

499
00:21:14,000 --> 00:21:15,760
that represents the fact that it

500
00:21:15,760 --> 00:21:17,520
has to do with the XY plane,

501
00:21:17,720 --> 00:21:19,620
as opposed to some rotated direction.

502
00:21:21,340 --> 00:21:21,900
Okay.

503
00:21:21,900 --> 00:21:23,160
So this is its definition.

504
00:21:23,500 --> 00:21:24,480
It's an operator,

505
00:21:24,480 --> 00:21:26,060
a linear operator.

506
00:21:26,940 --> 00:21:29,480
Associated with every linear operator is a matrix.

507
00:21:29,940 --> 00:21:32,060
The matrix associated with P

508
00:21:37,640 --> 00:21:40,760
is the matrix one minus one,

509
00:21:40,880 --> 00:21:42,260
as simple as it could be.

510
00:21:44,000 --> 00:21:46,130
And it's obvious now that when

511
00:21:46,130 --> 00:21:48,260
it acts on the vector X,

512
00:21:48,460 --> 00:21:50,420
let's let it act on the vector X,

513
00:21:54,120 --> 00:21:55,240
it acts on the vector Y.

514
00:21:55,240 --> 00:21:57,000
The vector X is represented by one,

515
00:21:57,000 --> 00:21:57,280
zero.

516
00:21:58,320 --> 00:22:01,020
That matrix times that column vector,

517
00:22:01,720 --> 00:22:03,100
one times one is one.

518
00:22:05,300 --> 00:22:06,840
Zero times one and one

519
00:22:06,840 --> 00:22:08,380
times zero minus one times zero,

520
00:22:08,380 --> 00:22:08,880
zero.

521
00:22:09,880 --> 00:22:14,460
So we see that the P observable,

522
00:22:14,580 --> 00:22:16,880
when it acts on the X vector,

523
00:22:17,020 --> 00:22:20,520
X polarization gives us back the X polarization vector,

524
00:22:20,520 --> 00:22:22,160
but when it acts,

525
00:22:22,160 --> 00:22:22,720
sorry,

526
00:22:22,880 --> 00:22:25,940
when it acts on the Y polarization vector,

527
00:22:31,480 --> 00:22:36,940
it gives minus the Y polarization vector.

528
00:22:37,220 --> 00:22:40,880
So this is the unique operator

529
00:22:40,880 --> 00:22:43,260
which represents the observable,

530
00:22:43,260 --> 00:22:49,700
the observable polarization

531
00:22:49,700 --> 00:22:51,140
in the X-Y plane.

532
00:22:52,240 --> 00:22:53,460
Now in this case,

533
00:22:53,600 --> 00:22:55,160
we knew what we wanted,

534
00:22:55,220 --> 00:22:57,320
we constructed the vectors,

535
00:22:57,620 --> 00:23:00,180
and then we made up an observable

536
00:23:00,560 --> 00:23:02,390
and we concocted it just so we

537
00:23:02,390 --> 00:23:04,220
would do what we wanted it to do.

538
00:23:04,540 --> 00:23:05,900
In other cases,

539
00:23:06,180 --> 00:23:08,120
and I'll give you an example of another case,

540
00:23:08,300 --> 00:23:09,620
in other cases,

541
00:23:09,660 --> 00:23:14,080
there might be reasons to focus on an observable,

542
00:23:14,080 --> 00:23:15,020
on an operator,

543
00:23:15,380 --> 00:23:17,760
and ask what its eigenvectors are

544
00:23:17,760 --> 00:23:19,100
and what its eigenvalues are.

545
00:23:19,100 --> 00:23:21,560
The example that I've already given you

546
00:23:21,560 --> 00:23:22,800
was for example the momentum.

547
00:23:23,460 --> 00:23:26,040
The momentum was described by an operator,

548
00:23:26,300 --> 00:23:27,500
minus I d by dx.

549
00:23:28,180 --> 00:23:30,040
I told you what the operator was,

550
00:23:30,300 --> 00:23:33,060
and then we found its eigenvectors and its eigenvalues.

551
00:23:33,660 --> 00:23:36,660
So sometimes it's more convenient,

552
00:23:36,820 --> 00:23:37,860
not a question more convenient,

553
00:23:37,980 --> 00:23:41,940
sometimes we know more about the vectors and the eigenvalues

554
00:23:41,940 --> 00:23:43,750
than we do about the

555
00:23:43,750 --> 00:23:45,560
mathematical structure of the observable,

556
00:23:45,700 --> 00:23:47,540
and sometimes we know it the other way.

557
00:23:47,540 --> 00:23:51,160
But either way,

558
00:23:52,980 --> 00:23:57,360
observables have eigenvalues and eigenvectors.

559
00:23:57,680 --> 00:23:59,780
The eigenvectors are the states

560
00:23:59,780 --> 00:24:02,040
in which the observable has a definite value,

561
00:24:02,260 --> 00:24:04,720
and that value is the eigenvalue.

562
00:24:06,200 --> 00:24:12,300
So we're back to the basic foundations of the subject

563
00:24:12,300 --> 00:24:14,440
and the postulates.

564
00:24:15,940 --> 00:24:17,500
We have an example.

565
00:24:17,540 --> 00:24:18,260
